animal.description:
Meet Lucy! She arrived at the shelter expecting and gave birth to two puppies. Fosters & Paws focusing on mama dogs and their puppies brought the family into safety. Pups are weaned, committed to forever families while Lucy is working on getting her figure back, ready for a forever family with shepherd experience. 

Lucy is delightful, but she needs structure and training to be her best self like all shepherds. She is super people friendly, wiggles her butt with her tail wagging non-stop, especially if you have a toy or treats for her. A busy girl, Lucy is ready to stretch her legs and get some much-needed exercise after lovingly caring for her babies and healing from her spay. 

Aged at 5 years, she is beautiful with her puppy bearing years behind her. Lucy will need some leash work, encouragement not to jump when excited. She is crate and potty trained. Showing way too much interest in fuzzy little things, no cats, small dogs, or critters for this strong girl in her forever home. 

Currently, she prefers to keep dogs at about a 2 -3 feet distance, which could be hormonal as her body is adjusting post-pregnancy. She is re-directed easily on a leash. At this time, it is unknown if she would be open to living with another dog.

If interested in Lucy, she is available through Fosters & Paws (www.fosterandpaws.org/adopt) for meetings with approved adopters with the recommendation to be a solo shepherd in her furever home. This is a courtesy post for our friends at Fosters & Paws following our evaluation of Lucy.

We do allow small dogs that are eligible to fly in the cabin of a plane. We DO NOT allow dogs to travel in the cargo area of the plane under any circumstances. animal.description:
Bernadette (formerly Princess) is a sweet senior beagle looking to be someones cuddle buddy. Shes around 8 years old and although this gal has been through a lot, she always has a cute little smile on her face. She has the most luxurious hound dog ears and makes little piggie noises when you cuddle her. She gets along well with other dogs but would probably prefer calmer dog friends. Bernie loves squeaky toys and is wild for treats and meals. She is working on losing some extra weight and making good progress, but will need a home that can continue to help her get into shape. Its a good thing that, in addition to being a couch potato, she loves going for walks! Bernie is mostly potty trained but will need some reinforcement in her new home. She also has a bit of separation anxiety when left alone so she would do best in a home with another dog or a person who is home most of the time and can help her work on her crating skills. Although Bernie is a lover, no cat companions for this gal please.

Bernadette's adoption fee is $195. Email your adoption coordinator if you are an approved applicant or apply today at rescuedohio.org to become approved!

animal.description:
Anders (previously Tucker) has landed at his foster home and is really coming out of his shell! He is about a year old and full of lots of love! He loves a good walk or play session with his foster fur siblings. He is good with other dogs of all sizes and even does well with cats! At the end of the day he enjoys cuddling up in his dog bed or on the couch with his people. He is going to need a family who has patience since this 70lb dude has a lot of fear about the world. He does have slight anxiety which makes it pretty hard for him to control his body, but with consistent boundary setting and schedule he will mold right into a home. He does well outside of a crate and can be trusted when left alone, you'll return to find him snuggled up in his donut dog bed or in the corner of the couch. A family with older kiddos (because of that puppy energy) and someone who has another fur baby would be best to teach him the ways of the world! 

Meet and greets can be arranged for approved adopters; apply today at rescuedohio.org or reach out to your rescue coordinator. Anders' adoption fee is $300.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Baxter! I am small but mighty! I am about 25-30lbs of sweetness that loves to give kisses. I am a little timid and shy at first but I am slowly but surely coming out of my shell. I enjoy playing with my toys and going for walks around the neighborhood with my foster parents. I am still working on my leash skills as I get excited for my walks but do tucker out easily with these little legs of mine. I'm hoping to go for longer walks as I get more acclimated from growing up in Texas. My foster parents don't know much about my past but everyday I like to show them something new, like my tricks of sit and shake! Although I enjoy hanging out and cuddles with my foster family, I also enjoy my space. I don't mind being in my kennel when you are away or sleeping, as I'm a pretty quiet and easy going guy. I am house trained and have had with no accidents. If you're looking for a little buddy, I could be your guy!

animal.description:
If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

***Thank you for your interest in Magnificent Mutts and Meows. We hope everyone is saying safe during this challenging time. Due to the current regulations set forth by Governor Pritzker on group gatherings we will not be having adoption events until further notice. As an all foster based rescue this means that all meets will be by appointment only. Your whole family must be available to attend the meet as there will be no second meets scheduled to help limit contact between our team and the public. To help streamline the process please make sure your current pets are up to date, you have landlord/HOA approval, and that you are prepared to take the dog home with you immediately before submitting an application. Thank you & Please stay safe!***

Paloma just arrived. She is approx 2 years old. GSD. She will be vetted and assessed so we can learn more about her. We know at this time she does need leash work so a fenced in yard (no chain link she can climb it!) would be ideal.
She is extremely shy so she will need a quiet home with a patient owner who is willing to work with her to overcome her fears. She is sweet and good with other dogs in fact another dog in the home will help ease her fears as well. Cats are unknown at this time. Any children in the home should be older and dog savvy realizing that Paloma needs her space and time to come around.

More information and additional restrictions may be added once she fully settles into foster care and we learn her full likes and dislikes.

If you are interested in adoption, please complete the Application to Adopt which you can find on our website (
www.magnificentmutts.org
) No phone calls please. Emails only.

animal.description:
MEET LEEROY!!

THIS DOG IS SLATED FOR EUTHANASIA by the County Shelter-- NEEDS IMMEDIATE FOSTER/ADOPTER.

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in it's possession. He is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4510410.

One of the saddest reasons a dog can be E-listed is because they are mentally breaking down in their kennel. This is what's happened to me. I am really struggling and it is inhumane to keep me here in this condition. I also did not pass my dog to dog evaluation at the shelter. Many dogs do not get along with other dogs....is this a reason to take my life away?...No!
Can someone save my life?

Leeroy has been a little mouthy at times at the shelter, but this is likely due to being stressed and overwhelmed at the shelter. He exits his kennel quickly and pulls moderately hard to the play yard. After just a couple weeks he became familiar with his go-to handler and is very friendly with him and leans in for pets. He really just wants to be loved, he is just scared at the shelter. Leeroy is only 4 years old and has a lot of life to live, and a lot of love to give! Are you the right home for Leeroy??

To meet me, please call 480 331 4188 or message us here. If you have a dog you need to bring down for a dog intro. Dog Savers has got over 230 E-listed dogs in the last year out of the shelter alive! A small percent of the donations go to our operating costs to help these dogs get out alive. Lets keep working together to save lives!!

If you are interested in saving this pet, please reach out via this link: https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/foster/BPAZ/Dog

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG.

Please visit our website for a complete up to date list of our available pets. www.fochp.org or visit our facebook for new arrivals. Please. only fill out the application if you are ready to adopt right now and have consent from all parties involved.This is Josie, she is about 13 years old and her owner has become homeless. She is very sweet and gets along with the male dogs she has spent many years with however, she does not seem to like new dogs. She is super easy and loving. If you are interested in meeting or adopting her please email fochp@yahoo.com Please fill out our online application (www.fochp.org). Once you meet the pet and decide it is the right pet for your family there is an adoption fee. The adoption fee includes the spay/neuter, age appropriate vaccinations, de-worming, microchip, 30-day pet health insurance which you will need to order when we provide you with the number. Our adoption fees are non-refundable so please be sure you are ready for a commitment to the pet you are interested in.
Once we receive the application, we can put you in touch with the foster home so you can schedule a time to meet the pet. Our adoption process is pretty quick, and a lot of volunteers are involved to ensure you get a quick response. Please. only fill out the application if you are ready to adopt right now and have consent from all parties involved. Once you submit the application please verify that it is received (the screen will say your application has been received) if you do not get that message it has not been submitted. - if you do not hear from us within 1 hour, we may not have received your application.

Adoptions are based on Best fit/match and then 1st come 1st serve. Please check your email regularly for a response from the foster and be prepared for the opportunity to meet the dog as soon as they can be adopted.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Did I catch your eye? Learn more about me by reading my profile below; I just might be your new best friend! Apply on our website
(

https://www.healingheartsrescue.org/adopt

)

to

set up a private meeting or check below for my adoption event schedule.

Age: Approximately 1 year old

Weight: 45-50 pounds

Dog friendly: Dog

selective - prefers calmer dogs her size - or best as an only dog

Cat friendly: No kitties please

Kid friendly: Yes, I love all people

Potty trained: Mostly, working on it

Crate trained: Yes

Fence: I'd love a fenced in yard, but not required

Hi I'm Java! I'm a beautiful energetic lady on the lookout for my new family. I love people and think everyone is my new best friend. When we meet I'll run to you with my tail wagging so fast you can't even see it. Watch out because kisses will be following this! I'm pretty sure I'm a lap dog because when it's cuddle time on the couch I'll be at close to you as possible. I'm currently working on lots of new things like leash training. I walk nice inside on it but pull outside because there's so many good things to smell and see. With some training I'm sure I could be a great hiking and jogging partner. If you have a fenced yard I could do my zoomies there! That would be so fun! I keep my kennel clean but will whine in it for a minute here and there. I want to be with my people. Can you blame a girl for wanting to be with her family? I'd also like to be your only baby so that I don't have to share your love. We all need a cup of Java in the morning, can I be yours?

Adoption Fee: $295

INTERESTED IN MEETING ME?

If you'd like to arrange a private meeting or begin the adoption process, please fill out an adoption application by visiting

https://www.healingheartsrescue.org/adopt

**Note on breed and age determination:

Breed and age are often determined on appearance, our own knowledge, veterinarian advice, and/or information from the sending shelters or previous owners. Most of our adoptable dogs were previously stray dogs with little history, we can't be 100% sure of a dog's breed mix, and unless there is a specific date of birth listed, we can't be 100% sure of a dog's age. Additionally, our assessments of a dog's interactions with other dogs, cats, or children are based on OUR experiences. Your experience may differ.

ADOPTION FEE INCLUDES:

Wellness check

Spay/neuter (puppies adopted with required spay/neuter certificate)

Age appropriate vaccines - rabies as required by law and distemper combo or proof of positive titer test

Heartworm test if over 7 months of age

Fecal test and/or deworming for parasites

Microchip



~ Healing Hearts rescue will also provide dental procedures, bloodwork, surgeries, and/or any other additional vet work as needed while dogs are in our care.

~ Adoption fees are non-negotiable and fees are listed on the dog's profile

~ Adoption fees can be paid the following ways with the required sales tax (7.525%) added:

PayPal

Credit Card

Cash

WANT TO HELP SAVE MORE DOGS?

Healing Hearts Rescue is a nonprofit, foster-based rescue

located in the Twin Cities area of Minnesota

that is 100% funded through adoption fees and donations

. We are excited for you to join us on this mission to save the lives of dogs in need.

We believe every dog deserves to be loved as true members of a family and are committed to fulfilling that dream one dog at a time! Sign up to foster, volunteer or donate on our
website

Healing Hearts rescue will also provide dental procedures, bloodwork, surgeries, and/or any other additional vet work as needed while dogs are in our care.

animal.description:
Many of you may feel like you know me already.  My name is Zelda and I arrived at AGPR on November 1, 2020. My previous owners asked their wonderful vet to take me in because I was only a year old and could not walk well on my back legs and they could not afford surgery.  I am so glad they did what was right for me - x-rays were taken and I was diagnosed with the canine version of torn ACL in both hind legs.

The wonderful people at AGPR welcomed me with open arms and scheduled my first surgery for the morning after I arrived.  And boy, were they surprised with my speedy recovery.  I felt like I could run a marathon a week after surgery (of course they refused to let me show them I could).  My second surgery is scheduled for my other leg right before Valentines Day, 2021.  I am hoping for another speedy recovery because I can NOT stand that silly "cone of shame".

Assuming all goes well, I expect to be released to go to my forever home sometime in April.  

I've been good around kids, but I've always been on a leash.  I am a BIG girl and once my leg is healed, I have a lot of youthful energy to burn.  Remember, I've spent the first year of my life not being able to run and play like a youngster. 

I've been told I am a pretty girl.  People love my markings and my sweet disposition.  I'm willing to start "interviewing" potential new families the first week in February.  It would be nice to know I have a family to go home to when the surgeon gives me the final "okay".

All Great Pyrenees require a fenced-in yard (at least four foot high). If you have questions about the breed or our adoption policies and procedures, please go to our website at www.agprescue.org.  There's plenty of good information about the breed on our website - Pyrs aren't a breed for everyone!

Our adoption application is online: http://agprescue.org/adoption-application/agpr-application-donations/  Please note that we are a small regional rescue organization.  We will consider adopting to families within a four to five hour drive to Richmond, VA

animal.description:
Puzzle is a friendly, happy, people-pleasing, 3.5 year old, 44 lb boy who wants as much love as he gives, which is a lot! We think he is a Terrier/American Bulldog mix. Puzzle likes car rides, snuggling, and chasing tennis balls. He is food motivated for ease of training, knows some basic commands, and is really good on the leash with a Gentle Leader headcollar. Puzzle will check in with you on walks to get a treat. He is about 95% house-trained. This sweet pup is not a high energy dog, but he will need a yard to play in, preferably with a fence, even though he will most likely want to do whatever you are doing, most of the time. He will do best in a home with older kids, 16 and up or adults only, as he is still learning how to play and might mistake small children for playmates. Well-socialized female dogs his size or smaller can be a good match for him, but he likes to get all the attention, so being an only dog would be just fine. Puzzle is crate-trained, neutered and up to date on vaccines and preventatives.

The adoption fee for this dog is $350 which includes routine vetting and spay/neuter. 

For more information, please contact Mandy at msmith@petconnectrescue.org

animal.description:
Mmmm, mmmmm!  Hazelnut is one sweet cup of goodness!  This bundle of joyous energy is bound to make one active family very happy.  

We can't say for sure everything that's in this sweetie, but her tail, coat, and appetite speak to Lab, her spots speak to a Heeler or Pointer (she does point) or both as does her brilliant mind and sensitive soul, and there is probably a touch of pittie in there for a touch of wiggle butt.  A better purebred mutt mix was never had.  

Hazelnut is about a year old and is around 62 pounds, so right at the top end of a medium-sized dog and the low end of a large-sized dog.  She is not great on leash yet (she thinks everyone just wants to have fun including on a walk), and she does believe she is a couch dog.  

This girl would be great in an active home that can give her exercise/walks.  She may inadvertently knock young ones over so, though she does love kids, resident kids should probably be old enough to stand their ground.  She gets along great with the large dogs in her foster home but her energy and desire to like everyone scares some of the small dogs.  Cats will probably not like her lack of boundaries when meeting a new animal but we do not believe she would harm them.  Hazelnut sleeps through the night in a crate and just wants to be loved.  

If you believe your home has been looking for a shot of sweet Hazelnut then read on or go directly to the adoption process page of our website, throwmeabondogrescue.org, to apply.  

All potential adopters are expected to complete an application and provide pictures of their yard, patio, and/or balcony making sure we can see the fence line and/or railing.  The application can be completed and submitted from our website - throwmeabonedogrescue.org - the link is found of the Adoption Process page.  Applications will be reviewed for approval before setting an appointment to come meet and possibly adopt the dog of interest.  In addition, those who live in a rental property are expected to provide proof that they are allowed to have a dog where they live.

Each of our rescued dogs has been de-wormed if necessary, de-flea'd (with topical treatment if old enough, and by medicated bath if too young), spayed/neutered, microchipped, is up to date on shots, and has been fully examined by a veterinarian.  In addition, each adopted dog comes with a starter baggie of the food it has been eating, a few treats for training purposes, a rawhide chew, a lead and collar, and a folder containing pertinent records.

animal.description:
OLIVE BRANCH CITY PARK DOG HAS SURRENDERED HIMSELF TO THIS HUMAN. 
Parker is scheduled to be neutered Wednesday, January 27th.  He will be heartworm tested, get his rabies vaccine and a microchip.
He is now safe and with save1pet in Olive Branch. No microchip. Not neutered, about 1 to 1 1/2 years old. Friendly. 
Was surprised he was dry after all the rain. Probably slept on a picnic table under one of the pavilions. He’s been out there since at least Monday, December 28th.
This guy is making progress today!  He was still so scared and trembling this morning every time I approached him to try and get him out of the kennel to go outside. I was determined not to force him and I think that paid off. I knew he had to potty and he’s old enough to know he sure didn’t want to mess his kennel. But he did. Within a half hour he pooped 3 times. So now I knew I had to get him out. I opened door and he approached and I slipped on the leash. He did amazing and out the side door we went. Lola was on the other side of the gate so he met her. He wasn’t sure about coming back in yet so I rotated Lola in and let Traveler aka Tiger, Sebastian, Reese out. Another good meet. 
So after getting kennel all cleaned up and fresh bedding n toys I worked on getting him back inside. Oh he wanted to so bad but in about 10-15 minutes he was in. Lots of praises for being such a good boy!  Progress slowly but surely. It’s a good start for the New Year.
We are only trying to make a guess on his breeds.
His adoption fee is $150 which will include his vetting.

If you are interested in adopting, we encourage you to fill out our adoption questionnaire at http://members.petfinder.com/~MS72/adoption_app.html

animal.description:
You can call me Saber or you can call me Sabre...I might respond.  What do you expect - I'm a Pyr!  We have very selective hearing.

I'm a sweet girl who is a bit reserved and cautious when meeting new people.  I do warm up quicker to women than men. The volunteers at AGPR have helped me learn that it is ok to trust other people and I'm getting better at it.  Slowly but surely.  

I recently spent a little time with a foster dad and he let me get up on his bed to relax.  I enjoyed that but found that the floor was a much cooler place to "chill".  I ride well in a car and enjoy taking walks.  I do pull a little - I think that is part of my nervousness when meeting new people.  But I love to run and play in the yard,

The volunteers continue to tell me I am a very pretty girl.  They say I have "maybelline eyeliner" and silver tipped ears.  They are so nice to me!

I'm not a city girl.  I'd really like to be in a calm home with a nice yard and an understanding neighborhood.  I will bark at strangers because it is my job to protect you and our property.

One last thing - I was in a home for a little while with cats and I DO NOT LIKE CATS.  Sorry...but it is important for anyone thinking of adopting me to know that.

All Great Pyrenees require a fenced-in yard (at least four foot high). If you have questions about the breed or our adoption policies and procedures, please go to our website at www.agprescue.org.  There's plenty of good information about the breed on our website - Pyrs aren't a breed for everyone!

Our adoption application is online: http://agprescue.org/adoption-application/agpr-application-donations/  Please note that we are a small regional rescue organization.  We will consider adopting to families within a four to five hour drive to Richmond, VA

animal.description:
Kiwi is a lovely little girl weighing in at 26 pounds and is estimated to be 9 years old. She’s completely up to date on her vaccines, heartworm and lymes negative, and spayed. Kiwi did have a rough upbringing, as she came from a hoarding situation where SWCHS had picked up 79 dogs in total. Because of this, she is not trusting of many humans, but does well with other dogs and even cats! Kiwi would do best in a home with only one other dog and calm cats, as she does like her space from other animals.

When Kiwi does choose a human she likes, she is their shadow and wants to be with them all the time. She loves to cuddle and be a lap dog, and is generally interested in everything her human is doing. She’s partially house broken, and walks amazing on leash. She’s not a very energetic girl in her older years, so playing is not a frequent thing for her. 

The best home for Kiwi would be a quiet one without any children, and only one person living in it. Realistically, having company over would not be an option.  Kiwi is very scared of new people, and does negatively react to any person (that isn't her owner) coming into her space. Due to this, during an initial meet and greet if Kiwi does not immediately make a connection, it is unlikely she will develop one over time. 

Any meet and greets will be done at the potential adopter’s residency, and cannot be more than a 35 minute drive from SWCHS. We will not be accepting any applications that do not meet the specific requirements for her adoption. If you believe that you have the correct home and lifestyle that Kiwi requires, please apply online today at www.swchs.com

He knows the sit command. Ace is not a fan of cats in a shelter atmosphere. Dogs are generally tested with dogs of their own size; and dog meets with the resident dogs are always encouraged. Dogs are generally tested with dogs of their own size; and dog meets with the resident dogs are always encouraged. Our cat test should be used as a general purpose screening only to rule out overt aggression; we always recommend caution when introducing dogs to cats in the home. Recommendation on suitability of placement with children by their ages is based on behavioral observations including energy level and response to body handling. We never recommend leaving young children unsupervised with dogs, and we cannot guarantee the behavior of dogs with children, other pets or cats. Behavior evaluations should be considered as a snapshot of the behavior of the dog at this point in time; JHS believes all dog families need to be prepared to invest time and energy into training as well as provide common sense management of their new dog. We always encourage family to do some research on the breeds or mixes of breeds prior to adoption as many can have some unique characteristics that may or may not fit into their families. Always remember that the majority of dogs at our shelter have been exposed to or may have kennel cough. Kennel cough is contagious to other dogs, please talk to your vet if you have any questions about kennel cough prior to adoption. Please ask your adoption counselor at time of adoption if you have any unanswered questions regarding illnesses and treatments of the path that you are adopting. animal.description:
Looking for a bonded pair of boys with lots of energy and full of silly antics?  Well, you're looking at them.  My name is Walter and my brother is Argie.  I am the handsome boy with black tipped ears and Argie is the good looking guy with the big smile.  He is such a ham - he sees a camera and lights up like a super model.  His smile is so big that his ears have to get out of the way!  You can see from the photos that I can be serious or show my charming personality when the paparazzi show up.

Since we were turned in to a shelter, our friends at AGPR don't know much about us.  We aren't telling them our age but they are correct when they say that we are "about two years old" (and we act it).  Since we are big and energetic, we suggest that there be no young kids in the household...we'd probably knock them over again and again and again.  We have not been tested with cats, but if it runs, we'll chase.  Its like Tag, right?

Please, if you live in a city environment, we aren't the right dogs for you.  We need some room to run and play and bark.  And we could use a forever home with someone who is willing to teach us some manners.  It is believed that we did not have much "parental guidance" in our formative.  But we are getting better!

We do prefer to be adopted together.  We were separated once for a week and Argie was not happy and kept trying to make his way back to me and I was depressed and cried.  I know, not very manly, but I missed him...alot!

All Great Pyrenees require a securely fenced-in yard (at least four foot high).  Depending on what kind of fencing you have, we may need a five foot fence. If you have questions about the breed or our adoption policies and procedures, please go to our website at www.agprescue.org.  There's plenty of good information about the breed on our website - Pyrs aren't a breed for everyone!

Our adoption application is online: http://agprescue.org/adoption-application/agpr-application-donations/  Please note that we are a small regional rescue organization.  We will consider adopting to families within a four to five hour drive to Richmond, VA

animal.description:
Domino!  Who needs pizza when you've got this cute little guy to join you for dinner?  (Well, he says go ahead and order the pizza and he'll share it with you.)  Domino is maybe around three years old, maybe younger, and around eight pounds.  He's probably a Jack Russell mixed with Chihuhuahua, but here he got his snaggle-toothed grin is beyond us.  

Scared as can be is how we found him at a shelter - too afraid to move a muscle and eyes that looked like they were going to pop right out of his head.  But it only took about five minutes for him to lie back, relax, and accept belly rubs.  In his foster home he has blossomed and become more and more confident, coming to be picked up and loved on.  Because of how scared he was we can only assume new people will need to give him a chance to warm up and may even experience his bug-eyes at first too, so he'll need patient people.

Domino has learned to love a crate and doesn't make a peep the whole night through.  He would do best in a new home if his people will continue to provide him that safe-haven while acclimating to a new environment.  He is not great on leash yet but it won't take long (thought he seems like he will be a dog whose idea of a walk is being carried).  Children 13 or older would be best as anything unpredictable will spook him.  He does get along with other small dogs but most large dogs give him a start so slow introductions or a home without any large dogs would be best.  Cats are okay and could probably scare the bejeevies out of him if they tried.  

If you have been looking for a small dog that truly is quiet and just wants to be loved and feel secure then this guy is the guy for you.  Read on or go directly to the adoption process page of our website, throwmeabonedogrescue.org.

All potential adopters are expected to complete an application and provide pictures of their yard, patio, and/or balcony making sure we can see the fence line and/or railing.  The application can be completed and submitted from our website - throwmeabonedogrescue.org - the link is found of the Adoption Process page.  Applications will be reviewed for approval before setting an appointment to come meet and possibly adopt the dog of interest.  In addition, those who live in a rental property are expected to provide proof that they are allowed to have a dog where they live.

Each of our rescued dogs has been de-wormed if necessary, de-flea'd (with topical treatment if old enough, and by medicated bath if too young), spayed/neutered, microchipped, is up to date on shots, and has been fully examined by a veterinarian.  In addition, each adopted dog comes with a starter baggie of the food it has been eating, a few treats for training purposes, a rawhide chew, a lead and collar, and a folder containing pertinent records.

animal.description:
Meet BG, a 7 yr old dalmatian mix rescued from a small shelter in Kern County.  She currently lives in a foster home with multiple dogs and gets along with everyone, big and small.  She even passed the cat test. She loves to play chase, especially when she's the one with the toy or the rope being chased!  She is a well behaved girl except for her counter surfing so some training on that, or blocking off the kitchen to her access, would be best .. she does love to eat!  She is very much a dalmatian in nature, very velcro, loves to be close, loves to touch and be touched by her 2 legged and 4 legged foster family.  She would be the perfect pup in a more low key home, calm and well behaved and always close by. She loves other dogs so would enjoy a multiple dog home but she does love her 2 legged foster family best and as long as she could be with her people, she'd be one happy girl.  She is spayed, vaccinated and microchipped so she's ready to go home any time the right home comes along.

If you are interested in meeting Ms. BG, please email Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc. at dalrescue@sbcglobal.net and provide your email so an adoption questionnaire can be emailed to you  You should also be able to access the questionnaire on line from the Dalmatian Rescue website homepage, www.dalrescuesocal.com.  Once the questionnaire has been completed and returned, and if it looks like BG might be a good fit for you and your family, a "meet and greet" can be quickly set up so you and your family and other dogs, can meet BG and see if there's a connection. She adores her foster family but would so love having a family of her own to love.

To learn more about Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc., a 501 c3 non profit charity, and to see all of our available dogs, please visit our website at www.dalrescuesocal.com.  You can also visit us on facebook at www.facebook.com/spottyfriends.  We love seeing posts and photos of life with your spotty (and unspotty) friends so please, keep them coming.  Thanks!

Jackson is a young 1.5-2 year old American Bulldog/Boxer mix. He is full of energy and personality. Jackson struggles with stranger danger and it takes a little while to warm up some humans but once he does he offers a lifetime of love and devotion. He loves cuddles and attention from the humans he trusts. Jackson is crate trained, house trained and knows basic commands like sit, stay, shake, watch and down. Jackson walks well on a leash but can pull occasionally. He has training in loose leash walking and meeting strangers. He will need a dedicated owner to reinforce these skills. Jackson loves treats and will do anything for cheese! Jackson does well with other dogs, but can be nervous around new people. He loves to play and would be best suited in a home with another well adjusted energetic adult dog. He may be able to live with cats but he will have to be introduced properly and monitored closely at first. Jackson would prefer a home with either no children or older children who can be respectful of him.

If you are interested in this pup, please fill out our foster/adoption application here: https://form.jotform.com/92587410679166 and someone will be in touch with you shortly!

animal.description:
Meet Mama Ambrosia! Here is her story.
Ambrosia was found running on a person's property very underweight and very pregnant. She came into rescue and our transporters thought she was in labor because she was so pregnant. Her foster mom kept a close eye on her for 7 days with no babies. On the 8th day, they decided it was time. She began labor in the morning however after several hours of labor and pushing it was clear something was wrong. A trip to Blue Pearl was taken to realize one of the babies was stuck in the birth canal. The vets gave her some meds to help her and she finally delivered her first puppy. That puppy unfortunately didn't make it. She delivered her second one there and it was healthy. So her foster mom took her home and she delivered 6 more babies throughout the night. Unfortunately another one passed but the other six were healthy. Sometimes we do not know these pups stories before being rescued and we don't know why certain babies do not make it. Fast forward a few weeks and this girl was being a wonderful mama to her babies. She did amazing. Now those babies are 11 weeks old and all went to their forever homes this weekend. Now it is her turn. Ambrosia is a lover, cuddler and just a all around good girl. She is fine with cats (with proper introduction, She lived with two in her foster home and was fine with them). She loves people, kids and other dogs. She wants to be a lap dog and although she is not a huge girl she is solid!!! She walks great on a leash. She can chew up a toy in seconds! Ambrosia is hoping to find her forever home with someone who will cuddle her, play with her and just love her. Think you want to give this girl a chance?? Apply today!

Ambrosia is up to date on age appropriate vaccines, dewormed, current on preventatives, heartworm negative, spayed and microchipped. Her adoption fee is $150. Just fill out an application to meet her at www.pawsitivetailskc.org!

animal.description:
Please note, RAGOM's adoption territory includes Minnesota, Iowa, North and South Dakota, and western Wisconsin within 75 miles of the MN border.   At this time, we do not adopt out of our territory.  

Princess is a Standard Poodle who was surrendered by a breeder in Iowa.  Her foster mom describes her as being SO SMART, sweet and a gorgeous athlete.  She runs, hops and floats when she’s in the backyard.  She loves tennis balls and will entertain herself with them.  Since she is a Standard Poodle, their breed tends to be highly intelligent and she requires exercise and mental stimulation with toys.

Princess does well on walks but does have a high prey drive so when she sees bunnies and squirrels, she will try and chase them.  Princess hasn’t had any accidents since arriving at her foster home, she is not destructive, loves her dog bed, and has free roam of the house.

Her only “vice” is counter surfing, not for food necessarily but anything of interest to her.  Princess has a cute trick, when you say “Cheese” she will give you a toothy smile from the left side of her mouth when she’s happy to see you.

Princess will need to be adopted with Buck, a 95-pound Golden Retriever, they are a bonded pair and Princess takes the lead on most things and Buck follows her.  

Their forever home cannot have other dogs as Buck is fearful of dogs he doesn’t know. They both have a high prey drive, so they require a physical fence and cannot live with cats. 

To learn more about Princess and to read her latest updates, you can see her bio at: https://ragom.org/dogs/princess-20-188

Placement Requirements:
Good With Dogs: With Buck
Good With Cats: No
Good With Kids: 13+
Fence: Physical fence required
Age: 8 years old

If you are interested in any of the dogs available at Retrieve a Golden of the Midwest (RAGOM), you can read our adoption process and apply to adopt, which can be found at: https://ragom.org/our-adoption-process.

animal.description:
Hi there! I'm Howie and I'm a 6 year old, 50 lb Aussie Shepherd/Chow mix. My human dad passed away and I spent 6 months in the shelter before the HIT Living  brought me in. I am an incredibly sweet, smart, sensitive and loving boy looking to spend the rest of my life with my forever person!!! 

- I am the BEST doggo: loyal, loving, affectionate, mild mannered, obedient and friendly! 

- My foster mom believes that my previous owner who passed, was connected to machines that beeped and I am forever traumatized by that. Every time something beeps whether it be a rice cooker, oven, or the laundry machine, I cry or bark. To calm me down, my foster mom calls me over, hugs me like a little baby and I cry in her arms while she tells me its ok. I then forget what just happened because I’m so glad to be getting pets and move on with my life! 

- I can be completely trusted when left alone! When my foster mom has to leave me, all of my foster siblings go in crates except for me because I’m the best boy that doesn’t chew or get into anything. I take a nap or work for hours to get that peanut butter out of that red thing, and it's all I need :) 

- The brown tears under my eyes remain a conundrum for my foster mom. The vet thinks its allergies but we’ve tried many different types of foods and I recently was put on probiotics and those seem to be helping! I will need to be on probiotics for the rest of my life which is a low cost my foster mom says! Don’t let those tears keep you from swiping next, I am handsome and when I look up for a treat I look like a puppy teddy bear!!! 

- I am an excellent sleeper and sleep on a dog bed next to my foster moms bed. I also do not jump on any furniture like my crazy foster siblings do, unless invited of course!

- My favorite things to do are go for walks, get pets (I’m still uncertain about belly rubs but behind my ears and my butt are my sweet spots, I also love nose kisses) chew on antlers, and just be by my person. I also love to walk right in-between my human's knees and wait for all the back and butt scratches they give me!

- I love car rides and if it weren’t too extreme, my foster thinks I would be a great camping dog!  

- I have one hind hip that is smaller than the other and that limits me to walks only (and who doesn’t love a good walk on the beach!). While I may never be able to handle hikes or jogs, I LOVE walks and my foster mom says I walk very well on a leash! I also know all my basic commands and am fully house trained. 

- I have foster siblings big and small and get along with them all. While I go to the dog park and doggie day care sometimes with my foster siblings (I mostly tend to keep to myself in these places), I would prefer to be an only dog and the center of someone’s world like I once was with my previous human. Even if I would never be resource guarding, my foster mom can see the sadness in my eyes when she is petting the other dogs because I am longing for that one on one attention all for myself. 

- Something must have happened to me when I was a little pup because I do NOT like being surprised from behind. Whether someone starts petting me from behind or brushing me without me knowing they are there, I can get really startled and snap back. That being said, I would do best in a home with no children ages 0 - 17 as they can be unpredictable, and whoever adopts me just needs to know to let me know they are there before touching me :) 

- Due to my Chow nature, I can be a bit mouthy when I get excited. A lot of people would mistake this for biting, but I would never bite too hard. That is just really how I express my excitement! 

- At my current foster home I go on 2 walks a day, to the dog park 3 days a week and doggie day care 2 days a week. Despite the disability with my hip, I live an active lifestyle and would like to remain as active as I am now, even if that’s multiple walks per day! 

- My ideal is home is with one or two adults that live an easy lifestyle, have no other dogs (or cats, I get really excited around cats and for some reason, they’re not as excited to see me), no young children, and a home where humans are around for most of the day or one where I can be brought to work. I do great meeting adult strangers and would make a great work dog as I would need a few potty breaks but happy to be laying by my person’s feet as they work. 

- I have been with my foster mom and dad for so long now, I would prefer time to get to know someone by having a few dates before I make the commitment for a full sleep over. If you’re patient and up for dating before we make it official, our love could last the rest of my lifetime!!! 

If you see me online I am still available for adoption! If you are interested in adopting me please fill out an application here: www.hitlivingfoundation.org/adoption-application, and email a video walkthrough of your home and yard to BOTH Nicole@hitlivingfoundation.org AND Marta@hitlivingfoundation.org. Your application will not be counted as valid without your video. You will hear back from us within a few days.

Like so many of you, I have been experiencing some challenges but I refuse to let them get in the way of living my best life. As you can see from the photograph, I look a little different from ordinary dogs. According to my foster family, I am a lot more special than ordinary dogs! It makes me blush to admit this, but my foster family says that I am bright and bubbly and bouncy. I enjoy spending time with both people and pups. I love toys! Playful and enthusiastic, I am able to get around on my two strong back legs better than some dogs can get around on their four good ones!
My doctor has recommended that I wait until I've grown into my big feet before being fitted for a prosthetic so I would ask you to please consider this should your heart yearn to make me a part of your family. In case you're wondering,

I get my good looks from my mom who was a beautiful German Shepherd mix and dad, that rapscallion, must have been pretty fuzzy and furry himself. I can't wait to meet the loving, patient family who is willing to find room in their hearts and home for me.

Buck spent his former life as a breeder dog and is now learning about the Golden life. He is a sweet, loving boy who his foster mom describes as a “puddle of love”.  He loves sleeping in his dog bed, he is not destructive and has free roam of the house.  He has yet to have an accident in his foster home.  He has learned how to walk nicely on a leash and his foster family is working on getting some excess weight off of him.

Since Buck spent most of his 7 years in a kennel he can be a bit weary of new people and needs a slow and quiet introduction which is why kids in his fur-ever home should be at least 13 years old and on the quiet side, without a lot of visiting friends.  

Buck will need to be adopted with Princess, a 48-pound Standard Poodle, they are a bonded pair and Princess gives Buck his extra boost of confidence when he’s hesitant about something new. 

Their forever home cannot have other dogs as Buck is fearful of dogs he doesn’t know. They both have a high prey drive, so they require a physical fence and cannot live with cats. 

To learn more about Buck and to read his latest updates, you can see his bio at: https://ragom.org/dogs/buck-20-187

animal.description:
There's no place like home...and Dorothy can't wait to get there! This beautiful gal has had a long journey on her way to her very own Kansas, but it's finally time for her happy ending! Dorothy is a beautiful 2 year old German Shepherd/hound mix who arrived at CCR with her siblings and parents from a shelter in Texas. Dorothy most likely spent her early months in a shelter with her canine family but not a lot of human interaction, so we sent her to foster to learn how to be a pet. Dorothy has simply BLOSSOMED! She started as a super scared dog who didn't want to be touched and now she's a friendly, goofy, playful, affectionate gal who LOVES her canine foster siblings, avoids her feline foster siblings, and ADORES all of the humans she meets. Dorothy has truly come into her own, and she's ready to find a home that will help keep up all the progress she's made.

To be happy and successful, Dorothy needs three things - 1) a friendly dog sibling who wants to play, snuggle, and frolic with her, 2) a spacious fenced in yard where she can party and have fun as she continues to practice leash walking, and 3) a crate because she loves her crate! We're fully expecting Dorothy to take a couple of days to adjust and acclimate to a new home, but based on how successful she was in her foster home, we're 100% confident that a few days of feeling it out and getting to know her new family will be all it takes! Dorothy is learning to walk on a leash and she's enjoying it more every day, She loves to romp in the yard and then beg for all the snuggles afterward. She's a real snuggle hog! She may enjoy dog daycare, dog parks, and other places where she can have fun with pups! Dorothy is great with kitties - she avoids the tough ones and happily co-exists with the friendly ones. Because she'll need a bit more time than usual to adapt to a new home, she'd prefer older kids and adults who can give her patience and space.

Dorothy truly has gone from a life of black and white to TECHNICOLOR! Come join in her rainbow!

To meet Dorothy, please submit an application at chicagocaninerescue.org.

animal.description:
Stella is a wonderful, complicated, affectionate dog. She is housetrained and respectful of the home, and is trusted with the majority of the house while her foster is at work. Stella is a low energy dog inside. Stella lives for belly rubs and dinner. She gets so excited for dinner that she respectfully dances every single night while it is served.

Stella was never socialized and has been in training for the past six months and has been doing well. She is leash reactive but is trained not to be, her new owners will need to continue her training in this area. Stella will require an hour to an hour and a half mentally stimulating walk daily. Stella is very intelligent, highly motivated by food, and very eager to please.

Stella is very wary of strange/new people and dogs. She requires proper careful introductions to both. For this reason, prospective adopters should have a safe place for her to stay in when guests are over. She is muzzled trained. Stella would do well with one or two similar sized well behaved dogs however other dogs are not required. Due to her prey drive she requires a home free of cats and small animals. Stella has bitten a home intruder before. Once trust has been established this dog is an absolute blessing to have in your life. Stellas foster will work with her adopters to ensure a smooth home transition.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Would not be good with small animals

animal.description: Hi there my name is Frankie nice to meet you! Because of how much I love your attention I would prefer if I was the only dog in the home. Small animals also get confused for toys because they are just so similar! I would probably do best in a home that does not have small children but I would be an excellent pick for a first-time adopter. I could see myself living in a home or an apartment and I would love to live a quiet lifestyle with my new family. I give off the most wonderful loving vibe and am just an all around great dog. I've got medium energy and a playful vibe so I would be happy running around and playing outside with older children, or just chilling on the couch with my new parents. I have a lot to learn as far as when and where to go potty and how to walk on a leash, but I'd learn anything to make you happy. While I am not potty-trained yet, I do keep my kennel very neat and I think I could master it in no time. I love balls and toys and fetch is my favorite game. I hope I'm cute enough to be your newest family member!

animal.special_needs_notes:
DOBBIE - UPDATE 1/29/2021:
Three year old Dobbie is still waiting for his forever home!! 
Dobbie is our gentle giant who is nearly blind due to PRA (progressive retinal atrophy, which is the degeneration of the retina, causing progressive vision loss culminating in blindness.) Once he knows his way around the environment, he navigates quite well. New places, new people, and other dogs need a slow, gentle introduction, as he can get startled easily. Dogs that come at him barking or lunging cause him great distress, making him feel the need to protect himself!  In general he is very easy going, though when in the vicinity of cats, he goes on high alert, so cats would definitely not be a good fit!!   While Weimaraners are known for being highly energetic and requiring lots of exercise, Dobbie is more sedate in character and overall doesn't require the level of exercise typical of the breed. He is crate trained and house broken, and fine to travel, or spend a little time alone in the securely fenced yard.  But he does love long walks on the leash, currently doing about two miles per day.  Dobbie would probably do best as an only dog in a household with family members who are sensitive to the need for him to be able to navigate without obstacles! If you would like to know more about Dobbie, contact us:  twcrescue@aol.com

animal.description: Meet Duchess! Duchess is a lovely 2-year-old mixed-breed gal who currently weighs about 58 pounds. She came to SFAS after her previous guardian could no longer care for her but now she is ready to find another loving family to call her own. Here at the shelter Duchess has been friendly and exuberant with people but can be picky about her dog friends so we ask that if you have another dog(s) at home to please let the scheduler know you will bringing them along for a Meet n' Greet. Duchess's adoption fee is $130. She is spayed, microchipped and has age-appropriate vaccinations. A licensing/microchip fee may apply. Interested in meeting with Duchess or being added to her waitlist? Please call (505) 983-4309 x 1610 and leave a voicemail message that includes the DOG'S NAME, plus YOUR NAME and A GOOD PHONE NUMBER - OR e-mail this information to adoption@sfhumanesociety.org. A scheduler will call you back within 48 hours to confirm your request. SFAS offers a variety of excellent training classes, seminars and Trainer Talks led by animal behavior professionals. These are $50 off for animals adopted from any shelter or rescue group! Due to current COVID-19 restrictions, classes and talks are all presented virtually using Zoom. For course descriptions, schedules and registration, visit https://sfhumanesociety.org/our-programs/behavior-training/group-training-classes/ for classes and https://sfhumanesociety.org/our-programs/behavior-training/special-seminars-and-workshops/ for seminars and Trainer Talks. To see more of Duchess click on the video!

animal.description:
Name: Ellie 

Sex: Female 
 
Color: Black and white
 
Eye Color: Blue
 
Birthday: 11/22/19 estimated 
 
Weight: 49 lbs
 
Large Dog Friendly: Yes, does well at dog park
 
Small Dog Friendly: Yes, no problems at all
 
Cat Friendly: No 

Crate Trained: Unknown. We haven't needed to crate her as we are retired and rarely leave the house...we will try when we get a chance.
 
Housebroken: Yes, no accidents at all so far! She is also outside a lot.
 
Energy Level: Medium high to high. She's a youngster! Loves to play!
 
Reaction to New People: She loves everybody so far...does tend to jump up on people, working on that.
 
Kid Friendly: Yes, doesn't jump up on smaller kids so far.
 
Training: Will eventually sit for a treat, comes pretty well when called we are working on that. Walking on leash involves a lot of sniffing and some pulling, but she does really well passing other dogs - even dogs barking in the yards we walk past.

Grooming Needs: Shorter coat stays pretty nice! Likes to dig once in awhile so dirty paws, but they clean up fast.

Fence: Has not tried to go over fence but will jump up on it to look at squirrels nearby. She DOES know how to open fence latches and lever door handles so a lock is needed on fence latch and locking of outside doors. She's a smarty pants :) 

Solo or Siblings: She has 3 foster siblings and she really enjoys their company! Would probably do best with another dog in the home

From the Foster: Ellie is such a sweetheart! She loves to play and run and is definitely a squirrel watcher. She loves her foster dad and when he leaves she does a whiny/crabby talking/howling combo thing that is precious and hilarious. She is a little awkward at times, not quite making it onto the bed or falling off the couch, and coming full speed running onto the deck and nearly sliding off of it! Plenty of energy, daily dog parks and playdates are needed. She likes her toys and chewie things but isn't aggressive at at guarding them. There have been a couple small spats at first but no problems lately - they've figured each other out. We are working on not being so nosy at the people's foods. She takes treats very gently and will eat ice for treats occassionally with our Echo. She is very good at bedtime, goes to bed when we do - sleeps on our family room couch with her puppy toy that she often uses for a pillow. Sometimes will sleep on the bed in the early morning. Doesn't wake you up too early to go potty or want to go outside in the middle of the night either. She is an absolute gem! Very sweet and lovable, loves pets and belly rubs!

Adoption Fee: $400

All dogs coming into Adopt a Husky Minnesota receive care tailored to their needs, including: Nose-to-tail exam with a partner veterinarian, Vaccinations (Rabies, Distemper, Bordetella), 4DX test to check for heartworm or tick exposure, Fecal Analysis, Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative, Spay/Neuter prior to adoption, Microchip, and are evaluated for temperament and trainability.

Finn is approximately 10 months old, is very social, has high food drive, is a big lover and a total goofball. He is crate trained and will cry from the crate if he has to go out, but is still working on housetraining. He does well with other dogs, cats and kids, although he does need to work on not jumping.

We are looking for an active home for him, someone who knows the breed, has another dog in the home (bonus for another dobi) and has a fenced in yard for him. If you do not meet these requirements your app will not be approved for a meet and greet. Also, he is not a dog meant for an apartment.

He is fully vetted (dewormed, core vaccines, bordetella, microchipped, neutered, on heartworm prevention and on flea prevention) and his adoption fee is $400.

To apply you must submit an app at www.islanddogrescue.net. All updates can be found on our Facebook Page at "Island Dog International Dog Rescue." If you are reading this profile he is still available and again to be considered you must submit an app, as we are extremely busy at the moment and cannot reply to emails or inquires sent.

animal.description: Gatsby is 2 years old and just shy of 80 pounds. Gatsby is a timid boy who would do well in a home as an only dog and with children 16 and up. Gatsby was one of 27 Weimaraners that GLWR took in from a seizure case in northern Michigan in November. All of these dogs have been in foster care for about 2 months. They are learning everyday - food bowls, leashes, toys and beds are all new experiences. Gatsby had a huge tumor the size of a small melon removed from his shoulder in late November. He has recovered beautifully. Rumor has it that he's been bragging and showing off his scar in the local dog park! Gatsby's Foster Mom Mary says "Gatsby loves walks and going getting pets when he goes to our local brew pubs. We didn't order him his own growler of craft beer but he did have a sip of my husband's pint! Gatsby enjoys having warm soft things to wear and play with; he really enjoys wearing a sweater. Gatsby's favorite toy to play with his his Bark Broccoli. Gatsby does not chew except for paper. He loved shredding his Christmas present paper, and then we discovered he shredded other papers that we left out by mistake. Its all gray to him. Gatsby likes to go hiking on trails, but can be fearful of other dogs. He is treat motivated and I believe training will give him some confidence. Gatsby loves sleeping in a human bed. He crates when he is home alone, but would prefer to free roam." Gatsby is healthy and ready to find his forever home.

PLEASE NOTE EMAIL: you will need to open your email account and type in the address because live links have been removed by Petfinder APPLICATION: If this dog has stolen your heart, don't wait! Fill out an application http://rescuedogvillage.com/forms/RDV/frm_adopt-rdv-cp.html to be considered as a potential forever home through our rescue. PLEASE NOTE APPLICATION: you will need to type the address in the address bar because live DOG NAME : IZZY RDV 937 DOG GENDER: Female AGE: 6 Months Old WEIGHT: 50-94 Pounds at Maturity BREED: German Shepherd LOCATION: Alabama Gulf Coast ADOPTION FEE: $550.00 (includes transport) EMAIL: For more information about this dog, contact email : ausman@gulftel.com EMAIL: For more information about this dog, contact: RescueDogVillage@yahoo.com APPLICATION: If this dog has stolen your heart, don't wait! Please apply online now to be considered as a potential adopter. FLOWING WHITE COAT WITH A SUBDUED SADDLE SPAYED, FULLY VETTED AND CHIPPED LEASH, BASIC COMAND AND HOUSE TRAINED GREAT WITH OTHER DOGS GREAT WITH PEOPLE Our German shepherd rescue is proud to present for adoption "Izzy", a 6 month old, female, white Swiss shepherd. Ms Izzy is exactly what you would expect a well-bred shepherd pup to be, wide open, full of life, inquisitive, happy, loving, smart and begging to train. This girl presently 52 pounds but judging from her build I would say that she will weigh 90-95 pounds as an adult. Izzy has great symmetry, perfect stride, gorgeous coat and a powerful, athletic, muscular frame. Our girl has passed all of our socialization and training programs, revealing a strong people drive, a strong affinity for training, high intelligence and a great social understanding with other dogs. If you have time and patience for a German shepherd puppy you not find a better example of the breed. About Our Rescue Whether you adopt through Rescue Dog Village Guardian, Inc A 5013c Non-Profit Organization or any other similar organization, the LEAST we can do is thank you from the bottom of our hearts for considering welcoming these deserving dogs into your hearts and home. One of our favorite sayings is "RESCUE IS THE BEST BREED," and we believe that wholeheartedly. Help us help these dogs and submit your application today! We appreciate that you want to help make a difference in the lives of dogs who need us most!!! RESCUE ROCKS! Disclaimer: Please note that the breeds posted on our dogs' biographies are our best guess based on years of working with rescue dogs. Adopters who need to know the exact breed or mix of breeds of a particular dog must have the dog's DNA tested at their own expense.
To see more photos of this dog and all our adoptable dogs,
please check out our website at Rescue Dog Village.
RESCUE DOG VILLAGE GUARDIAN, INC A 5013C NON-PROFIT ORGAINZATION WEBSITE: WWW.RESCUEDOGVILLAGE.COM OUR DOGS ARE MICRO-CHIPPED AND READY TO BE PART OF YOUR FAMILY TODAY! These dogs deserve all of our attention, and in Rescue Dog Village Guardian, Inc A 5013c Non-Profit Organization, we are committed to our adopters and our dogs equally. We offer full disclosure and hope to make the best matches possible. Please know our adoption fees never cover our expenses. We rely on the generosity of our adopters and supporters to help us help the dogs. Our rescue is only in the business of offering full disclosure to adopters, and expects and hopes to engage your questions and concerns fully. We owe it to the dogs we rescue and all the wonderful families/adopters who might consider welcoming our charges into their hearts and home. Our dogs are waiting for that ideal forever home where they will be cherished as deserving family members. It's sad these second chances are even necessary for these dogs, but we are committed to them and will devote the time and energy to their re-homing, and not just move them to save more dogs. We diligently and responsibly seek good matches, as we don't want to re-home the dog again. These animals have already endured more than they should have, and through no fault of their own. It behooves us to be honest and forthright, and we appreciate the same in return from applicants. It's that winning combination of reciprocal trust and respect that allows for successful placements to be made. Happy adopters translate to happy dogs, and that's our goal!

animal.description: Meet Titan! Titan was rescued off the streets as a puppy, found next to his mamma who had been poisoned. He is now about 8 years old, and loves to meet all people including kids although he may be a bit much for smaller children as he weighs around 95lbs. He needs a proper introduction to any new dogs he meets, and sharing a home with smaller dogs, cats, or other animals may not be best suited for him. An ideal person or a family would be an experienced dog owner who is confident in handling dogs his size, and willing to do some training so he can be the best version of himself. Titan is a gentle giant who loves to snuggle and give kisses to his people. He is house trained, calm around meal times, and enjoys going on walks. He rides awesome in the car and has a patient, loving and easy going personality. He’s a big lover who has been waiting for his forever family and a comfy bed to call his own. Titan was rescued from Ciudad Constitucion, Mexico, and is being fostered in Portland, OR. Will you be his hero?  If you are interested in Titan, the first step is to fill out an application at www.streetdoghero.org/forms

animal.description:
Leah is a full blooded Tennessee  Treeing Brindle.  She was adopted from a shelter and driven to Indiana.  Two days later she was surrendered to the Marion-Grant County Humane Society.  Leah was confused, frightened, and scared.  It took several weeks and this lovely lady is finally out of her shell and ready to find her forever home.  Leah seems good with other dogs, wants to play so bad, is friendly and loving.  She would make a great addition to any active family.

The Marion/Grant County Humane Society encourages potential adopters to research dog breeds before adopting.  All breeds have certain care, training, working, feeding, and space needs.  Check with your local library, book store, veterinarian, or shelter for more information.  Make sure the dog you adopt will be the perfect match for your family.  

    The adoption fee is $150 for puppies(less than 18 months of age), $130 for adult dogs(greater than 18 months of age), and $50 for seniors(dogs 8 years of age and older)  which includes the spay/neuter surgery, microchip, dhlppc accinations, deworming, and flea prevention.  If you are interested in adopting this animal please fill out an application, go online to  complete one at http://www.marionhumane.com/application or come in to our facility to pick one up.     

    We do check all references thoroughly so please make sure all phone numbers are correct.  Applications take 5-6 days to review depending on weekends/holidays.  

   Please be patient as we strive to send each of our animals to a forever home.  
   
     We are a non-profit, no-kill animal rescue shelter known as Marion-Grant County Humane Society and are not affiliated with Marion Animal Care and Control.

Hello, my name is Sheba. I am 8 months old, female, bulldog mix, current on vaccinations -rabies, distemper/parvo, dewormed, spayed.

Sheba was brought to the shelter by an angel who rescued her from being outside, on a chain. Sheba could not be any happier, sweeter and more cheerful dog. She loves other dogs and does great around cats. Just like any other puppy, she is very affectionate and playful, but Sheba is just so special. Given where she came from, it is amazing how she came out and how incredible she is.

Adoption Fee $ 475
This tax-deductible fee pays for the vaccinations, spay/neuter, boarding, food, and overall care of all the animals at the shelter.

(*Includes spay or neuter with HHP vet. If a personal vet is preferred a partial refund will be issued. KEEP ONLY IF NOT FIXED)

**If you're unable to adopt, please consider donating or volunteering your time to these deserving animals currently living at HHP. They require care and love on a daily basis, which adds up monetarily. Our shelter is funded by donations and adoption fees alone. The need is great within our community and your support matters.

If you have questions, please stop by any day between 1pm-6pm. Contact our office at (406) 896-1700 or Angie (406) 860-8735.

Meet our new rescue Rover! He is a 2 year old neutered and vaccinated German Shepherd/ Australian Shepherd mix! He is very playful, he loves playing with toys and jumping up to give everyone kisses!

He likes to nudge his nose against you and pull your arm with his mouth for attention. Rover is not good on leash when seeing other dogs, he will bark and lunge at them but with proper training he will listen. He does not understand boundaries so he will need a dominate owner.

He does bark a lot when he wants something or when he’s in a crate. He is a high energy dog, so he loves his walks and going for hikes. He is very smart and treat driven. He knows sit and shake a paw.

animal.description:
Hello World!  My name is Duramax, but calling me Sunshine is much more appropriate.  I am a 2-year-old mixed breed male with snow white hair and adorable black spots.  My foster mom thinks I look like a fuzzy plush stuffed animal!  

I LOVE LOVE LOVE toys... If it squeaks and I can chew on it - I'm a happy boy!  I love to play tug of war and fetch (sometimes I even bring it back!).  I'm not a huge fan of sharing my toys at first, but if you give me some space to trust, I will start bringing you my toys so we can play together! 
I love long walks because I enjoy new smells and new adventures.  While I'm a curious boy, I'm non-reactive on a leash when other dogs and people walk by.  I have also played with other dogs at the shelter's playgroup, so I am open to making new friends.  

I'm a fun-loving boy that has a smile on my face when I wake up in the morning and when I go to bed at night.  I have a lot of energy and get the zoomies A LOT!  My dream is to have a big backyard where I can run, play and be the puppy I am. Despite never having a real home, I am very respectful in my foster home.  When left alone, I don't scratch, rip or tear anything up, and I'm house-trained!  My foster mom says I'm a super smart boy!  Anyone would be SO lucky to have such a smart, loving and beautiful boy like me.
to adopt Duramax contact; AFLAR. allforloveanimalrescue.org and fill out an adoption application. 805-445-3535

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Danika. I came to this shelter after I was abandoned with my 4 pups. The only information that was given to the shelter staff was a note with my age, my pups birthdays, and the reason for abandonment was because they were moving and could no longer keep us. I am very skiddish and fearful, so I will need a very patient, experienced adopter. The staff can tell that I want to trust people, but it is very difficult for me given my history and the fact that I am in a shelter. I would love to find a loving family that will be patient, give me the time to learn to trust them, as well as understand that I will more than likely always be skiddish and fearful. I do like to play with stuffed toys by myself, and I loved playing with my pups, but they have all been adopted. I get along well with most other dogs, and it would probably be best for me to go into a home with other dogs so they can show me that I can trust people. I could also benefit from being in a home without dogs if it is with someone who is home a lot and will work with me slowly. I have not been around cats, but the staff does plan on interacting me with them to see how I do. If you would like to meet with me, or if you have any questions, please ask staff.
                                                                         Love,
                                                                         Danika

animal.description:
Gretzky is the man! Don't be fooled by this guy's senior status, he could pull a carriage if he wanted to! He really does it all, he plays hard, he eats well, and he sleeps like a rock (he's also an excellent cuddler). Gretzky does have a lot of energy though, so he is hoping his adopters love to go on walks (lots of them). His perfect adopters would be active, with another dog-friendly dog. An adopter who can spend a lot of time with him would be great, because he loves his people.

Age: 11

Breed: Pug

Weight: 38 lbs

Kid-friendly:
Loves kids, but does jump, so we would advise no young children. He has lived with kids ages 6+

Dogs: He's great with dogs

Cats:
Unknown

Crate trained:
Gretzky does not like being in a crate. He barks, and blankets covering the crate are not advised. He can be left in a crate for up to 6 hours, but would prefer to be out and about.

Potty trained: Yes!

Likes:
He LOVES multiple walks a day, being outside, lounging around, eating, and his people!

Health concerns:
Gretzky has a small fatty lipoma under his right arm. Gretzky also has Lyme Disease, but does not show signs of lameness.

Adoption fee: $375

Our dogs receive heartworm and flea/tick prevention the first week of each month, March through November. Dogs that have stage 3 or 4 dental disease will receive a dental procedure in rescue. We aspirate all lumps and remove those that our veterinary partners suggest removing.

Adopters will be responsible for continued preventatives, follow-up appointments, and medications (if applicable).

$50 discount for seniors (65+) and veterans. Adoption fees help pay for the dog's veterinary exam, vaccinations (rabies, distemper, and bordetella), HW test, blood panel, a microchip, and spay/neuter if needed and additional health needs specific to each animal.

You can apply to adopt at www.greyfacerescue.org/adoption-application

Want to bring me home? It's easy! All you have to do is fill out an application on our website: acadianaanimalaid.org/adopt/dog-adoption/application 

Our adoption fee is $225 for puppies and $205 for adults . All AAA dogs are up to date on all vaccinations, spayed or neutered, on heartworm preventative, and microchipped. 

Dogs are individuals -- The shelter software system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of our dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We encourage you to select your new companion by considering each dog's individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on a breed label that is only a guess.

animal.description:
Jubei is a 1.5 year old Pit Bull Terrier mix who is all muscle at 55 pounds. He is as sweet as can be! He knows basic commands, is house trained, and does well in the crate. He loves walking with his foster family, but could use some work on the leash-he's a puller!

This sweet boy lost his owner to cancer and was well-loved and well cared for. He's adjusting well, but looking for a family that can provide the love and stability he's used to! Jubei was raised with another dog in the home and was in a foster home with another dog, but Jubei does like to guard his food and toys and would need an experienced dog owner who can manage and watch this behavior.

If you are interested in adopting Jubei please submit an inquiry directly with Greater Charlotte SPCA by visiting charlottespca.org/adopt.

***Because our rescue is composed entirely of volunteers and we require a home check for each of our adoptable pets prior to them going to their new homes, local applications will take precedence. We will accept out of town applications, but any family further than 60 miles from Charlotte is responsible for finding a representative of a rescue local to them that is willing to perform the home check. All out of town applicants will also have to be willing to drive to Charlotte to meet/pick up the pet as soon as the application is approved.***

IF THIS LISTING IS STILL VISIBLE, THIS PET IS STILL AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION. PLEASE DO NOT EMAIL US JUST TO ASK IF IT IS STILL AVAILABLE!


Say hello to Squiggy! He is about 4 months old, and as sweet as they come! He is UTD on vaccines, parvo negative, de-wormed, and on heartworm and flea prevention. He is currently about 25 lbs.  He will likely be 45-55 pounds at full maturity.

Squiggy was picked up as stray by a good Samaritan, who then contacted us for help. He is playful, loving, and full of energy- your typical puppy!

He will NOT be neutered prior to adoption. Believe it or not, we get this question about our young pups quite often. Pups this age are far too young to be altered. That will be the responsibility of the adopter once the pup is of age (approx. 6 months).

We will not be doing meet and greets prior to adoption dates, due to COVID-19 regulations.

If you are interested in adopting, please fill out our adoption application FIRST! We expect a surplus of applications, so please allow 2-3 business days for a response once your application has been submitted.

If approved, once we receive confirmation that you wish to adopt, you will be asked to pay your adoption fee up front. This will place the puppy on hold for you until the scheduled time for pickup. We will send an invoice the same day as your approval. This is our policy due to the overwhelming number of no-shows and last-minute cancellations that have happened in the past. If you decide not to adopt upon meeting the puppy, your fee will be refunded in full before you leave our office.
However, if you do not show up without prior notice, you will forfeit any fees that you have paid.

You can access our application on our PetFinder homepage, or on our Facebook page as the top pinned post. You can also copy and paste the link below!

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSeqyYWJx1_Q63jZ22u-IhaXZ9x0aT5THc5WPpP1BGe0-zSfxg/viewform?usp=sf_link

Thank you for reading about this sweet pup, and we look forward to meeting his new family!
