animal.description:
Hi friends and future family. I'm Ragna, the viking pittie of lore. You may recognize me from when I was first adopted as a puppy named Jasmine. In the 2.5 years since my adoption (I'll be 3 in May 2021), I've learned a lot. I've developed a love for food and am extremely motivated by it. I've developed a love of toys, especially rope toys. I've learned a lot of basic commands and like to show them off for food. I enjoy sun bathing and hanging out with my people. I love traveling. My mom says I've never met a stranger. While I've been learning about all these things I love, I've also learned I'm not comfortable around young kids. Now that there are infants and toddlers around, I'm deciding I'd prefer an adult only home. Or maybe one with teenagers, since we have things in common like a love for food. My family has reached out to my rescue to help me find that new home. One where I can just be the me I was always meant to be. Can I be me with you?

Ragna in a nutshell:

Likes: toys (especially rope toys), food, hanging out with big humans, sunbathing, traveling and car rides. 

Behavior: has not had much interaction with other dogs (though she lives with a senior small... we're not yet ready to declare she's dog social), cannot be homed with cats, uncomfortable with toddler and infant energy. 

Skills: knows basic commands (sit, stay, come, and wait), crate trained, house trained, walks well on leash and does well with getting groomed

Medical: allergic to chicken, sensitive skin

Ragna is currently in Temecula, CA but is looking for a foster or forever home in LA, Orange County, or surrounding areas.  To meet Ragna please visit our website and complete an application- https://k9kismet.org/forms/

Nala is a strong, active dog who enjoys long walks, hiking, water play and tough toys when she is comfortable with her humans.  She doesn't trust people easily but once you're in her circle she explodes with confidence.  Her adoption program will allow interested parties to meet her during several visits with Nala and our Canine Program Manager.  
Nala needs to be the only pet in an adult home with few visitors.  She is wary of new people, doesn't enjoy meeting strangers and will need a family who understands her need to retreat to a safe spot, especially when it's time to do yard work.  She would do well with a fenced yard so she can play daily and perhaps take a dip in a pool when the weather is nice!
Please call/email for an appointment to meet this gorgeous girl!

Female - 2 years - 50 lbs - Microchipped - Spayed - PAHello! I'm Sugar! I am a 2-year-old, 50 lb spayed female. I am already housebroken and crate-trained, although I am a lady who does not need to be crated when left home alone. I enjoy having the crate available for me though.
I am a friendly girl with men, women, and children! I love to give people kisses, especially new people and can be enthusiastic in greeting! I am loving and will happily cuddle on the couch with you. I will welcome new visitors into the home.
I am not friendly towards other dogs or cats and will need to be the only pet in my home. I like toys and will play fetch with you!
I currently only pull slightly on the leash and I love car rides! I am happy to go out and about with my people.
I am a happy girl looking for my perfect home where I can be the center of my people's attention is that with you?
Follow me on Facebook: #EchoDogSugarTX
For more information, please contact adoptions@echodogs.org.

Echo Dogs fosters dogs in many states. Visit www.echodogs.org/available-dogs to see more of our dogs. Transportation for the adopted dog IS available. Remember, we are an all-volunteer foster rescue organization - we DO NOT have a physical shelter to visit. Our minimum adoption donation is $300. All dogs are spayed/neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations and micro-chipped. Puppies under 6 months old may not be spayed/neutered. This would be the responsibility of the adopter at their own expense. Proof of spay/neuter will be required!
To review our adoption procedure and submit an online application, visit: www.echodogs.org/procedure

This very handsome young boy is King and he is a doll - just a very happy boy! He loves to play with other dogs and really likes people too. King had the misfortune of ending up at a crowded Animal Control and he was so frightened there so they reached out to us for rescue help. King is now doing so well in foster. He loves playing with all the dogs there and gets along so great with everyone, big and little. He does fine with cats although he will probably try and get them to play with him, and even seems to like the horses, too. He is just a big fluffy playful guy who would do best with another dog to pal around with. King is very puppy like, bouncy and playful. He does walk well on leash and seems eager to learn new things. King is just a nice guy looking for a great home of his own. He is currently 80 pounds and may have more growing to do. When he came into rescue he had a slight limp but xrays showed nothing at all wrong and he runs around just fine now. He will be a great companion for some lucky family. We are not sure if he has lived indoors before or was another discarded farm dog but he should fit right in well with any situation - he's a sweetie!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY. View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Due to COVID-19, CITY DOGS is currently doing adoptions by APPOINTMENT ONLY. Please visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog to request a meet and greet! 

Questions? Email: citydogs@city.cleveland.oh.us | Call: (216) 664-3476
Visit: 9203 Detroit Avenue Cleveland, OH 44102

Hours:
10 AM - 3 PM Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday
10 AM - 6 pm Tuesday & Thursday

Fee: $61 | Includes spay/neuter, shots, microchip, license, 30 days free pet insurance (when registered upon adoption)

The CITY DOGS mission is to increase adoptions from the City Kennel by changing the image of the pit bulls who make up the majority of the kennel population, by preparing all adoptable dogs in the kennel for lives in loving homes and by creating as many opportunities as possible for the public to meet and get to know our dogs for the terrific pets they are meant to be.

Our Adoption Process...
Here's a little about how things work:
All of the CITY DOGS posted for adoption are available for direct adoption from the kennel, unless noted otherwise. You must schedule a meet with a dog in advance - we are not currently accepting walk-ins. Please look online first to see if there are any dogs you think would be a good fit for your home before scheduling a meet. To get the process started, visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog and fill out the form. One of our adoption counselors will get in touch to schedule and confirm your meet! At the kennel, an adoption counselor will introduce you and your family to the adoptable dogs, share information we know about them, and discuss our suggested ways for successfully integrating a new dog into your home. You are welcome to meet multiple dogs. If the dog you adopt is already fixed, he or she may leave with you that day - otherwise, the dog can go home after receiving the spay or neuter surgery.)

About Our Dogs: All available dogs have gone through a behavioral and medical assessment. This assessment is a snapshot of who the dog is at that given time. We cannot make any guarantees with regard to behavior, temperament or health of any City Dog once they are in the home. Most of our dogs are picked up as strays, so we do not know what kind of home environment they were living in (i.e. with kids, other dogs or other cats), nor do we know if most of them are house trained. Everything we know about them is based on volunteer and staff observations. We do have some dogs in foster homes, where they will have more information about how the dog is in a home environment. It is very hard to tell with certainty whether or not a dog will be good with kids, cats or another dog. If you have kids in the home or another dog, we do require that they be present for a meet and greet with the dog you are considering for adoption.

Heath/Vaccinations: Dogs that are adopted directly from the kennel need to go to your personal vet within two weeks of leaving the kennel. All dogs receive their DAPPL, Rabies, and Bordatella vaccines, though you may be required to get follow up boosters. All dogs come microchipped and with a Cuyahoga County license.?

animal.description:
Abby
Terrier - Papillion Mix (This is our best guess, again we don’t know for sure, since she was a street dog) .
2-3 years old - (This is the vet’s guess based on her teeth)
15 lbs

No cats - she barks at them

Dogs okay - her size - she barks at big dogs but likes to play with dogs her size.

Older kids -  over 12 years old, she is shy and can be timid of new people. No babies or young kids.

She does ok in the car, but doesn't love it. 

Abby is looking for a home where can be spoiled with attention. She can be jealous of other dogs in the home, so being the only dog in the home would be best, but Abby can totally have dog friends and play dates or doggy day care! Abby also loves to snuggle with you and wants to sleep on your bed at night with you! 

Abby want to be adopted by people who are home a lot to give her lots of attention.   She loves chasing after squirrels in the backyard and exploring. Abby is super curious! She can sometimes get barky at action she sees through the front windows (cats, squirrels, etc) so no apartments or condos. 


She’s doing so well learning how to walk on a leash and will be a great little walking partner.


Abby will need a quite forever home with a fenced backyard and will peoples that will continue her positive reinforcement training and socialization with people.


Adoption fee is $550 - that covers all of the vaccines (DHLPP, Rabies and Bordetella), current on flea/tick treatment, fecal testing, deworming, sterilization (spay/neuter), Heartworm-Lyme-Ehrlichia-Anaplasma Blood Test, dental cleaning (if needed), Distemper and Parvo blood test to make sure the dog is disease-free, Health Certificate, Microchip with registration, grooming before transport and the flight transport from Guadalajara, Mexico to Portland, Oregon. We will also send the dog home with a brand new collar, ID tag, leash and a small bag of the kibble. 


Fill out an online adoption application here: www.BAPBR.org


*Please know that we are a 100% volunteer ran organization, with no paid employees and we work full time jobs and have our own families to care for as well. Due to the large number of applications we receive - we are not able to reply to everyone individually. If we think you are the right match for our dog, we will reach out to you and set up a meet and greet. Thank you in advance for understanding.

To apply to adopt Cooper, please fill out an application at https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/25488/generic (copy and paste into address bar)

Cooper is a stunning boy who, at 57 pounds, is a great big lovebug. He has a sweet disposition, walks well on a leash, is fully housebroken, and gets along with other dogs and seems indifferent to cats although care should be taken during any introduction. We do not know what his breed mix might be, he looks like a textbook Presa Canario but half the size.

Cooper is currently down south with one of our rescue partners and has been brought up to date on his shots and neutered. Cooper is undergoing heartworm treatment. Once he has been certified heartworm negative, he will be able to come north to his new home, Due to the treatment he's undergoing it most likely will be in March.

Cooper must go to a home that is experienced with mastiff breeds and is set up to accommodate this type of dog. Please read up on the breed before applying. Due to his size, Cooper should not go to a home with very young children.

If you are able to open your house and heart to this big softie and can wait until he's able to come north in March, please submit an application and we will get in touch with you.

animal.description:
This is Tucker. Tucker is almost two years old and about 60#. He is fully vetted and hw negative.

Tucker was rescued by an elderly couple off the street. He was skinny and starving and they have nursed him back to health. He is way too big for them to keep and so they have asked for help in finding a furever home.

Tucker is currently living with 2 cats and a small dog comes to stay every few weeks, and he has no issues. He loves to go on walks and never barks on walks. But he does pull to get closer to the pups. When dogs bark or lunge at him. he pulls away. He is crate trained. 

He’s an odd guy, very friendly and loving, but needs breaks and kinda shuts down sometimes. He has some reactivity to the doorbell/knocking but is otherwise VERY friendly with people. Has gotten better impulse control with training (jumping less, fetch, waiting at doors..)

Tucker has not been around kids. Only on walks and he loves to watch them. He suckles his dog bed at night and loves chasing squeaker toys. 

Now for the bad: He is an anxious dog. He gets easily worried. He does need to be sedated to get his nails trimmed and has had a few ear infections.
He has allergies that he was getting shots (apoquel) for but the vet now thinks it’s from food so they’re experimenting with his diet.

Application and meet and greet required.

Application available under the adoptables tab at www.pawsa.org

animal.description:
I have an Adoption Pending and will be going home soon! I hope you will consider one of our other wonderful dogs in need. Thank you!

Pretty Sasha spent three weeks, at the City of Mobile Shelter in AL, where she was taken in as a stray.  Being a black dog, she was passed by time and time again by prospective adopters. No one took her home, as happens all too often to black dogs, no matter how sweet and loving they may be.  When we learned what a good girl Sasha is, we took her into Sunshine to find her a forever home.

Sasha is estimated to be six years old, weighs 65 lbs, and is most likely a purebred Black Lab. Our lead Southern volunteer, Lisa, was so impressed with Sasha when she met her, remarking that Sasha is prettier than her pictures show and that Sasha has the sweetest personality.  Sasha loved the soft stuffed toys that Lisa brought her as well as treats and being petted.  She is a little shy when first meeting new people but warms up quickly.  Sasha liked the other dogs she met at the vet clinic, nosing up politely for a sniff and a hello.  She has not had an opportunity to meet cats. Sasha's coat is very shiny and she has a nice moderate energy level.  We think she will be so happy to be someone’s walking partner and special girl!

Sasha is spayed, vaccinated, and micro-chipped.  She is completing heartworm treatment and will be ready to travel to a new forever home in mid-February. 

Rescued dogs come with a range of needs - from behavioral to emotional to medical.  When approved applicants adopt such dogs, they agree to continue the rehabilitation we have begun.  

If you would like to be part of Sasha's rescue story, and you have already been approved for adoption through SGRR, please contact the Adoption Committee at: CandyVS2@aol.com      to be considered to adopt sweet Sasha.                  

If not yet approved for adoption, please visit our website to learn more and to submit an online application:     http://sunshinegoldenrescue.com/adoption-info1.html  

Please DO NOT use the ASK ABOUT button to contact us, about this dog, as that will delay our ability to respond to your inquiry.  Please direct any questions regarding your application status to:  ajpillinger@gmail.com     

Thank you!
 
ABOUT OUR RESCUE 
Before being approved to adopt, all potential adopters will be required to complete our online application and participate in our pre-adoption review process. The process includes the completion of an online application, a reference from the applicants' vet, a phone interview, and a visit to the applicants' home.  The application process helps us determine what type of Golden would be best suited for the applicants' life style.  In some cases, the specific dog you are interested in may have found a home before this process is complete or further assessment may indicate that this dog is not the right match for your family.  We are frequently getting new Goldens in need of a home, so we encourage you to apply and complete the application process so that when the right dog comes along you will be ready. 

The information provided on each dog is based on the observations of our vets, volunteers, fosters, and when available, trainers. While we do our best to report any and all issues, SGRR does not make any guarantees as to the health or temperament of any dog. Dogs evolve differently in different environments and we cannot predict with any certainty how the dog you adopt will behave and adapt in your home.

SGRR ADOPTION FEES - Effective May 1, 2020  (subject to change)
  
  $750    Puppy - up to 6 months              
  $650    Young 6 months - 6 years            
  $550    Senior 7 - 9  years                       
  $450    Senior 10 years and older          
 
  $550    Young Special Needs                
  $400    Senior 7+ Special Needs                

$1000    Young Bonded Pair                   
  $900    Senior 7+ Bonded Pair         

A contract is signed on the day of adoption.  Under the terms of the contract, all adopters are required to bring their SGRR dog to a vet within 7 business days.  All dogs receive basic veterinary care prior to adoption.  However, if an adopter's vet identifies an illness that an adopter is not willing to treat, then the dog may be returned and a full refund would be provided. 

Most of our dogs are fostered in private homes.  We do not have a facility to visit.  We are committed to our dogs before, during, and after adoption! To this end, the rescue retains an interest in each dog and our dogs can never be surrendered, re-homed, or sold. Should an adopter no longer be able to keep their SGRR dog, SGRR must be notified so that we can take the dog back into rescue and place it into another home. We reserve the right to remove a dog at any time should we find the adopter is no longer providing proper care.  Adopters agree to follow up visits as needed.  

Please be a ray of light for this Sunshine dog and make a tax deductible donation toward medical care and other expenses.   Every cent of your generosity goes directly toward the care of a Sunshine dog.

Please visit our website at: http://sunshinegoldenrescue.com  to learn more about our rescue and to make a Donation to support Sunshine Golden Retriever Rescue.  

THANK YOU!

animal.description:
Stormy is a precious female toy poodle about 1 year old and 7 pounds. She was brought to us by a good citizen who found her as a stray. We were unable to locate her owner and are looking to place her into a good home. 

IF YOU'RE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS DOG:
Please go to our Website: Poodlerescueofhouston.org and see the section: "Steps 2 Adoption". There will be a drop down menu where you must read and meet all of the prerequisites. Next, read the "Steps To Adoption", fill out the "Interest Form" and submit it online. THIS IS THE ONLY WAY TO APPLY. Unfortunately, we are unable to respond to inquires made in any other way.

Poodle Rescue will contact you if we feel this dog, or a similar dog in our program, matches the specifications on your Questionnaire/Interest Form. Please keep in mind Poodles and Poodle Mixes are in high demand therefore the demand for them far outweigh the supply. If you do not hear from us please re-submit your Interest form quarterly as they are not recurring. Unfortunately, we cannot answer email or telephone inquiries about our available dogs.  Please be sure you have a current phone number listed on the questionnaire/Interest Form and the best time we can reach you. Adoption Fees vary.

All dogs are spayed/neutered, current on shots, parasite / heart worm disease tested (and treated if positive).  All dogs are microchipped, groomed and use a dog door at our facility.

animal.description:
Betsy Bucket is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet her.

Betsy Bucket is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~6 years 
Weight: ~57lbs
Housebroken: Working on it! She needs to be on a strict schedule and due to her steroid meds she needs to go out a little more frequently. She currently goes outside 4-5 times per day. 
Crate trained: Working on it! Takes some time to settle but overall doing well with her crate training
Dog sociability: Friendly with dogs on walks
Cat sociability: Unknown
Kids: Friendly with kids!
Ideal home: Betsy Bucket has an autoimmune skin condition that requires lifelong medication. She is looking for an adopter that can provide her meds and keep her comfortable!

Betsy is a sweet and calm mature dog. She's a great companion on long neighborhood walks and loves a belly scratch and her comfy napping spot inside her crate. She will play fetch if it's nice and warm out and loves lounging in the sun. She has done amazing with the young child in her foster home and would likely make a great family pet. We have seen incredible improvement with her autoimmune skin condition over these last few months and are hopeful that it will only continue to improve! Betsy is such a sweet dog deserving of a wonderful forever home.

Betys Bucket's adoption fee is 300. She is spayed, up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative. Betsy has been diagnosed with Pemphigus foliaceus, an autoimmune disorder affecting the skin. Small fluid-filled blisters form, which can rupture easily and cause lesions/infection. Pemphigus folieaceous can be treated/managed with lifelong steroids and dermatologist-recommended medications/treatments. Betsy has shown extreme improvement since beginning steroid therapy. Adopters should be prepared to continue treatment with private veterinarian and potentially with a dermatologist. 

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***

animal.description:
Gus is a 6 Year old American Staffordshire terrier that adores his people.  Probably weighs around 60 or so pounds. He is a big goof ball that loves snuggling on the couch and going out on a leisurely walk around the neighborhood.  He hasn’t been around other dogs much so he’s very cautious and growls if they get too close. So we think that he will do best in a home with no other animals.   He’s coming into rescue because his family can not manage their children and a dog, at this time. The toddler is unfortunately bugging him and he doesn’t appreciate it. Therefore,  we would love to find him a family with older kids that can listen and be respectful, when around him.  He is fully house trained, doesn’t chew inappropriate things and he’s kennel trained.  His current family has given him the run of the house when they are away from home, and he’s done just fine.  But, we recommend crating him for the first few weeks, as he adjusts to new surroundings.  Changing homes can be a little stressful & unsettling.  If you’re ready for a big hunk of love in your life, please reach out to us about our Handsome boy. He will be your best friend for the rest of his life.

We will be setting up meetings with a $50 deposit that goes towards your adoption fee if you adopt. We are also doing video of interior and exterior of home in lieu of the homecheck. 

We are a FORCE FREE rescue. The adoption contract you will be signing specifically states that you agree to NEVER use any aversive methods nor tools like a shock, prong or choke collar. We are never sure about breed because we do not do DNA (we make our best guess), so if that is important to you, this dog may not be the right choice for you. Please, consider everything when making a decision to adopt a dog.  As part of your adoption package, each dog will be fully vaccinated (Da2PP, Rabies), have a microchip, and be spayed/neutered. You may need to come back to us to complete shots, spay or neuter, hw test. You will receive 6 mths of HW preventative.You will receive a free bag of premium food, as well as a gift card from Choice Pet Market if you live in one of the designated zip codes . Training is MANDATORY and will be scheduled at a later date and place.

Welcome to the Wonderful World of Rescue Dachshunds. Look around and read their bios. Find a few whose personality seems to fit well. Consider one of our Well Seasoned Seniors who are truly wonderful and have so much to offer. Need help finding the best fit? We'll help with that too. Please fill out an application and let's get you all matched up with a loving new "furever' companion and friend. You'll find the application on the "Available Dogs" page.

NOTE:

Adoptions to Central/South Texas residents only

Standard Adoption Fee Adult Dog: $250 ea. Puppy Adoption Fee: $300 ea. Reduced rates for Seniors dogs (10 and up). Reduced rates for pairs (when adopted together). All adoption fees are subject to sales tax per the State of Texas. DDRTX only adopts in Central/South Texas.

Email: ddrtxinfo@gmail.com Primary Website: www.DDRTX.org
NAME: DONATELLO

KNOWN ALIASES: LITTLE DONNY, LD, DONNY

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: HANDSOME RED CHIWEENIE

ALLEGED CRIME(S): BEING TOO CUTE, A REAL PLEASURE TO BE AROUND, THE GOODEST BOY!

OBSERVED BEHAVIOR(S): VERY TIMID AT FIRST AND THEN BLOSSOMS INTO AN EXTREMELY GOOD BOY, LOVES A GOOD NAP, FOLLOWS HIS FURRY FRIEND'S LEAD, WOULD PREFER TO BE WITH/NEAR HIS HUMAN AT ALL TIMES, PREFERS TO GO OUTSIDE FOR HIS BUSINESS, GETTING BETTER AND BETTER ON A LEASH, HAS A HEALTHY APPETITE, ENJOYS BELLY AND EAR RUBS, WOULD RATHER SLEEP WITH HIS PERSON, RESPONDS WELL TO POSITIVE REENFORCEMENT, A GOOD LEARNER, SMILES WHEN HE SLEEPS, LOVES ON HIS HUMAN MORE AND MORE AS HE GAINS CONFIDENCE IN HIS SITUATION

RECOMMENDED SENTENCE: ADOPTION! FILL THAT PAPERWORK OUT!

Little Donny would probably prefer a quieter environment. He does well with other dogs and adults although he prefers minding his own beeswax, uncertain about other animals and children. LD currently chows on Taste of the Wild Pacific stream and various snacks (cheese, unseasoned meats, coconut, etc.). Donny doesn't care for loud bangs or rushing vehicles so having his own yard may be better, but will do just fine if he can't have that. Donatello is a very sweet boy, fill out that adoption paperwork and schedule a meet today!

Donatello did test positive for tick born disease but has been on medication. He will always test positive for it but may never have any issues with it. The vet has cleared him for adoption. Put your application in today!
Love dachshunds and not ready to adopt or circumstances won't permit having a dog? How about being a sponsor or making a donation. Every one of our dachshunds receives excellent medical care along with day to day food, love and housing. Being non-profit, we rely on generous individuals like yourselves to help save these fur babies. You can do this specifically for one dog with the sponsor button on their webpage or a general donation on our "How To Help" page. Easy and quick through Pay Pal or your debit/credit card. You generosity is sincerely appreciated by all and is tax deductable. Need other ideas? You'll find tons of them on the How to Help tab. All contributions are tax deductable.

Diamond Dachshund Rescue of Texas is a non-profit 501(c)(3) volunteer organization with focus on rescue and adoption of pure breed Dachshunds. All dogs are fully vetted and housed on private property. Meetings are scheduled upon adoption approval. Thank you for your continued support to the rescue and shelter communities!
Opt to Adopt!

animal.description:
01/13/21 MEET "LITTLE MISS MATTIE WIGGLE BUTT" a.k.a. MATTIE
Mattie was brought into BR- NWA's care on October 24, 2019 from NE Arkansas. Weighing in at only 35 pounds of skin and bones, she was a very sickly little boxer girl suffering with severe intestinal problems, chronic diarrhea, ongoing digestion issues, and as if that wasn't enough, she was also heartworm positive. 
If you wonder why you haven't seen much about Mattie on Facebook, it's because at first she was just too frail for adoption, and BR volunteers were down to a bare minimum with hardly a minute to spare for the few volunteers to make Facebook posts or fundraise for her care. So, Mattie basically "lived" at the veterinary clinic until November 13, 2019 when the rescue’s long-seasoned and highly dedicated volunteer, Denise, couldn’t help but bring Mattie home to nurture her during the extensive heartworm treatment. Little did anyone know what a challenge this would be as Mattie had a severe allergic reaction to the heartworm treatment medication which forced a different treatment plan that has not been fully successful. (More on this topic in subsequent posts.) Bear in mind that these are the early, intake photos of Mattie when she first came into Boxer Rescue NWA’s care. 
Mattie's veterinary expenses, special foods, medications, and ongoing vet care has not come with a small price tag, but she has been well worth the $3,437.71 of care which “wiped out" boxer rescues' meager savings. We estimate that with her final vet visits, medications and expenses, her total vetting and care will exceed $4,000. 
As most of you know, this rescue group is a no kill, 501(c)-3 nonprofit. We are an all-volunteer team and receive no funding from any animal rescue organizations such as the ASPCA, Animal Rescue League, Humane Society, etc. - these organizations do not typically help local rescues, nor do we have wealthy contributors or corporations keeping us afloat. We function solely on the donations of boxer lovers like you and us. 
If you can find it in your heart (or wallet) to help with Mattie's extensive health care needs and expenses, this striving rescue can replenish its much-needed resources and open the door to other boxers desperately in need. A tax-deductible donation of any amount, even just $5 or $10, adds up to make the difference in the life of one more boxer in need. 
STAY TUNED FOR MORE ON MATTIE, ADOPTABILITY, AND UPDATED PHOTOS OF HER TODAY!  jc/dm

01/13/21  MORE ON LITTLE MISS MATTIE WIGGLE BUTT a.k.a. “MATTIE”
So, here we are, 14 months later, and Mattie is closer to being free of the microfilaria - we'll know after her next checkup in early February if it's successful. If successful, this little sweetie pie will be available for adoption! 
Though Mattie no longer has adult heartworms, it is the heartworm larvae (microfilaria) that has been incredibly resistant to die.
Thanks to our dedicated volunteer, Denise's TLC and persistent care, her MANY trips to the vet for Mattie treatment and follow up, her attention to bringing Mattie to full health, this "pup" has "fattened up" nicely, and as you can tell by the pictures, she looks amazing!! 
Some of our rescued boxers have had to be in long-term care due to the severe state of their health upon intake. However, we hope that soon, Mattie will be available for adoption into a well-deserved forever home if the microfilaria continues to diminish. 
ABOUT MATTIE'S TEMPERAMENT: 
A little cautious around some men (timid), Mattie has no issues with women or children. She gets along with other dogs and is a sweet, affectionate, happy, 50 lb. spayed boxer who loves to be with her people. Whether you’re going for a ride, walking at the park or just cuddling on the couch watching tv - she's all in! 
If you have ever considered adopting a rescued boxer, remember to submit your applications soon (and include the vetting records of your current pets showing they are current on vaccines and heartworm prevention.) If you have already submitted an application, be sure to let us know your application is on file and any vetting records on your current pets. 
Mattie is small boxer who has been a funny, loving companion. Her loving foster "mom" has nurtured this little "wiggle butt" to become the beautiful, healthy, gentle girl that she is.
We hope you don't mind us posting this message again, as we are desperately in need of resources (volunteers and donations), and we invite you to join the rescue team as a foster volunteer. Please comment and/or share this post.

Welcome to the Wonderful World of Rescue Dachshunds. Look around and read their bios. Find a few whose personality seems to fit well. NOTE:

Adoptions to Central/South Texas residents only

Standard Adoption Fee Adult Dog: $250 ea. Puppy Adoption Fee: $300 ea. Reduced rates for Seniors dogs (10 and up). Reduced rates for pairs (when adopted together). All adoption fees are subject to sales tax per the State of Texas. DDRTX only adopts in Central/South Texas.

Email: ddrtxinfo@gmail.com Primary Website: www.DDRTX.org
Scrappy Cotijo is an energetic Chiweenie pup. He had a loving, but difficult start to life and is now on his way to being just like any other puppy.

Scrappy Cotijo loves running, playing, and chewing. If he's not going on zoomies or terrorizing a toy, he's snuggled up on your lap... or your head; he's quite the climber. Scrappy Cotijo is an absolute cuddle bug and loves being around his people. If you're looking for a new playmate and shadow, Scrappy Cotijo could be your boy.

He hasn't had the chance to interact with kids, but would probably do well.

Scrappy did test positive for tick born disease and is on meds for it. He will always test positive but may never have any issues with it. The vet has cleared him for adoption.

Love dachshunds and not ready to adopt or circumstances won't permit having a dog? How about being a sponsor or making a donation. Every one of our dachshunds receives excellent medical care along with day to day food, love and housing. Being non-profit, we rely on generous individuals like yourselves to help save these fur babies. You can do this specifically for one dog with the sponsor button on their webpage or a general donation on our "How To Help" page. Easy and quick through Pay Pal or your debit/credit card. You generosity is sincerely appreciated by all and is tax deductable. Need other ideas? You'll find tons of them on the How to Help tab. All contributions are tax deductable.

Diamond Dachshund Rescue of Texas is a non-profit 501(c)(3) volunteer organization with focus on rescue and adoption of pure breed Dachshunds. All dogs are fully vetted and housed on private property. Meetings are scheduled upon adoption approval. Thank you for your continued support to the rescue and shelter communities!
Opt to Adopt!

animal.description: This beautiful boy is Bodie.  He is about 10 years old and weighs around 70 lbs.  Bodie has cerebellar disease so he's very wobbly when standing or walking and sometimes even stumbles and falls.  He can walk with support from a harness and will soon be getting his very own wheelchair to assist in his mobility and allow him more freedom to sniff and explore which he loves to do! Bodie needs a human who is strong enough to support him at times with the harness (or help get him in and out of a wheelchair) and who is patient with him during feeding time and walks as he takes longer than your average pup. Bodie also needs a home with a fenced in yard. He loves nothing more than sitting outside in the grass near his people. He will slip and fall on tile floors, so area rugs or carpeting are a must have for him.

Meet Maui! Maui is currently enrolled in the P.A.C.K. Program, a 9 week intensive program for routine obedience, agility, and handling training with a prison inmate trainer and he is almost ready to show off all that he has learned to new adopters. His new skills include 'sit', 'stay', 'down', 'shake', 'wave' and more! New adopters should realize that PACK Program graduates will require regular, ongoing reinforcement of learned behaviors in order for them to become permanent.
Maui is a sweet, timid boy. He is apprehensive with new people and in new situations. It will take a little patience to get him used to all the new people and things he will encounter in his life. Once he knows his human is good people he can't get enough affection and loves to be close to his person. Until he trusts you fully, calm corrections for any undesirable behaviors are most effective. Anything more will overwhelm him. Maui plays well with all the other dogs in the program, he can be a little nippy at times but this behavior is easily corrected with a verbal redirection. As with any new dog, monitored play time is recommended until you get to know him better. Maui should not go to a home with cats. He is house trained and crate trained as well.
Maui is set to graduate the first week of February. This timid guy would love to be your new best friend. It must just take a little time to convince him that you're the one. Apply to meet him today and show Maui what the good life is all about.If you are not viewing this adoption listing from our website at www.bdar.org, please go there to get more information, find our adoption application, or submit an inquiry. Our pets are listed for adoption on multiple pet listing sites and we do not always have control over whether those sites are regularly or accurately updated. We also cannot guarantee we will receive forms or inquiries submitted through these 3rd party sites. For questions, call us at 307-514-4024.

animal.description:
*PLEASE read Oliver's write up ENTIRELEY as he does have special needs and is seeking a specific home!*

Oliver is a spunky Catahoula mix that is about 2 years old and weighs 50 pounds. who is loyal to his people. He enjoys long walks with lots of opportunities to sniff, morning snuggles before everyone gets up for work, and the occasional all-out run (he has some of the funniest zoomies you'll ever see). He is house broken and knows all the basic commands (sit, down, stay, paw, roll over) and is currently learning the place command. He is super smart, eager to please, and food motivated. While he loves being with his people, he's also perfectly content snoozing on the couch during the workday until his pawrents get home.

Unfortunately, Oliver's beautiful blue eyes don't work very well and he's completely blind in his right eye and mostly blind in his left eye (he can likely just see blurry shapes). He's seen a vet and ophthalmologist who have confirmed that it's a neurological issue and, while he's not in any pain, the impairment is permanent and his vision will continue to deteriorate.
Due to his vision issues, Oliver is very fearful of new people. He must go to a quiet, adult-only home with limited visitors that will help reassure him that he is safe and loved. At least one other confident dog in the house is a must, as well as a fenced in yard (preferably a privacy fence) as he's never really done a lot of around-town walking (although he is good on a leash). He currently lives with two cats whom he's curious about and occasionally chases but they live in harmony together 95% of the time - the other 5% the cats just hide on an elevated surface. His adoption fee is a donation of your choice and includes he is neutered, microchipped, and up to date on all vaccines, flea/tick treatments, and heartworm preventative. If you are interested in adopting any of our animals please fill out an application on our website www.lastchanceranch.org

animal.description: 2 - 3 year old Daisy was surrendered to a shelter by her owners when they felt she needed medical care that they could not afford.  She had never seen a veterinarian until coming to rescue.  She will be seeing our doctors soon, and will be available for adoption very soon thereafter.  Daisy's owners told the shelter that she appeared to have had some sort of "seizure", but neither the shelter, nor AHGRR has seen any to date.  However, this will be thoroughly investigated by our doctors.  Daisy is very sweet, and very "puppy".  She does fine with the other dogs as long as she is not totally mugged by them when meeting them for the first time.  She LOVES people.  She does need some training, though she appears to know the command "sit".  Daisy has decided to accept applications now so that when she is ready to leave (around the 2nd week of February), her new person will already be chosen.  If you would like to offer Daisy a forever home, please submit an application which you can find on our website (www.almostheaven-golden-retriever-rescue.org)

animal.description:
Axel is a cute little senior that needs a family that knows how to respect his space. He just came to the shelter after being in a home for 7 years (at no fault of his own), but is having a hard time adjusting. He can be nervous throughout handling, but does allow petting once he is more comfortable. He also does not  like his food and chews touched, so he needs a family that is willing to work on this with him using positive reinforcement and one of our recommended training programs.

While he does have some things to work on, once he is comfortable he loves being cuddled in bed, getting treats, and going on walks. Give this sweet boy a chance!

Axel's age recommendation is 12 years of age and up. He is currently around 8 years old.

animal.description:
We aren't too sure exactly what breed Majorie could be, but we are sure that she's adorable! Miss Majorie is from Arkansas, and she is a little bit shy. She's friendly and wants attention/petting, but needs people to go slow so she doesn't get frightened. We highly recommend a positive reinforcement training program to help her build her confidence and strengthen the bond with her family. Once she's comfortable, we see her being a total lap dog that can also be your exercise buddy! She can be selective with other dogs, so dog parks would not be a good idea. She seems to prefer people anyways!

Majorie's age recommendation is 6 years old and up, and kids must know to go slow with her.
